@@TJvErrorProvider
<TITLEIMG TJvErrorProvider>
JVCLInfo
  GROUP=JVCL.??
  FLAG=Component
Summary
  Provides a user interface for indicating that a control on a form has an error associated with it.
Description
  Use an error provider when you need to notify the user about an erroneous input value in a non-intrusive
  way. The error provider uses the real estate of the form or dialog to display icons next to each control that
  has been determined to have an error. The icons Hint is also assigned the specific error message so when the user
  moves the mouse over the icon, the reasn for the error is displayed.

  Although mainly used to display erroneous user input, this component can be used whenever you want to draw
  the users attention to a specific control or set of controls without having to show a dialog or similar.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvErrorProvider.BeginUpdate
Summary
  Suspends screen repainting.
Description
  The BeginUpdate method suspends screen repainting until the EndUpdate method is called. Use BeginUpdate to speed processing and avoid flicker while
  errors are added to or deleted from the component.
See Also
  EndUpdate
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvErrorProvider.BlinkRate
Summary
  The rate at which the error image should flash.
Description
  Use BlinkRate to specify at what rate the error icons blink. The rate is expressed in milliseconds and the
  default is 250 milliseconds. A value of zero sets BlinkStyle to ebsNeverBlink. If BlinkStyle is ebsNeverBlink,
  this property have no effect.
See Also
  BlinkStyle
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvErrorProvider.BlinkStyle
Summary
  Specifies how blinking is performed.
Description
  Use BlinkStyle to specify how the error icons are blinked. For more information on the possible values of BlinkStyle,
  see the help topic on <LINK TJvErrorBlinkStyle, TJvErrorBlinkStyle>.
See Also
  TJvErrorBlinkStyle
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvErrorProvider.ClearErrors
Summary
  Removes all error icons.
Description
  Call ClearErrors to remove all error icons handled by this component with one call. After a call to ClearErrors,
  the internal error image list is emptied.  Calling ClearErrors is the same as setting Error[nil] := '' but
  is slightly faster.
See Also
  Error
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvErrorProvider.Controls
Summary
Provides indexed access to the internal, protected list of TJvErrorControl instances.
Description
  Use Controls to get direct access to the TJvErrorControls that are maintained by the component.
See Also
  Count, TJvErrorControl
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvErrorProvider.Count
Summary
  Returns the number of controls in Controls.
Description
  Read Count to determine the number of TJvErrorControl objects in the Controls array.
See Also
  Controls
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvErrorProvider.EndUpdate
Summary
  Re-enables screen repainting
Description
  Use EndUpdate to re-enable screen repainting that was turned off with the BeginUpdate method.
See Also
  BeginUpdate
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvErrorProvider.Error
Summary
  Provides indexed access to each controls error messages.
Description
 Use Error along with the AControl parameter to access the error message associated with a control. Setting the error message to an empty string removes the error image
 (this is the only way to remove an error image for a single control).
 <AUTOLINK OFF>
 Use <CODE>Error[nil] := 'SomeValue';</CODE>to assign the error message 'SomeValue' to all controls. Using
 <CODE>Error[nil] := '';</CODE> is equivalent to calling ClearErrors but ClearErrors is faster. <AUTOLINK ON>
See Also
  Controls
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvErrorProvider.ImageAlignment
Summary
  Specifies where the error icon should be located.
Description
  Use ImageAlignment along with ACotnrol parameter to specify where the error icon should be located relative to AControl.
  If AControl is nil, ImageAlignment is set for all controls.
See Also
  ImageIndex, Error
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvErrorProvider.ImageIndex
Summary
  Soecifies the image to display.
Description
  Use ImageIndex along with the AControl parameter to set the image to display for ACotnrol. If AControl is nil,
  the ImageIndex is set for all controls.
See Also
  Error, ImageAlignment
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvErrorProvider.Imagelist
Summary
  Lists the images that can appear on the error icons.
Description
  Images contains a list of images that can appear on the error controls. Each error controls's
  ImageIndex property determines the specific image displayed on it.
  If Images is unassigned, no images are displayed on the error controls.

  Images in the list can be of any size, the error control will automatically adjust it's size
  and position. To accommodate every system on which your application runs, it is recommended
  that you do not use 256 colors or higher.
See Also
  ImageIndex, TJvErrorControl.ImageIndex, TJvErrorControl.Imagelist
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvErrorProvider.ImagePadding
Summary
  Specifies the padding around the images.
Description
  Use ImagePadding along with AControl to make minor adjustments to the location of the image within the
  control. If AControl is nil, ImagePadding affects all controls. If ImagePadding
  is 0 or less, the image is centered within the control. 
See Also
  ImageAlignment
